179,-0.02636658,0.03185607,0.01115752,0.00214251,0.03716043,-0.02803564,0.11693493,0.01838433,0.01214491,0.00896145,-0.00177753,-0.02882246,0.04859446,-0.04016909,0.03119075,-0.02193180,-0.06395379,-0.05543075,0.03136891,-0.04218573,-0.01604315,0.03008917,-0.05191761,-0.00384548,-0.02798944,-0.00364366,-0.01231767,-0.02448582,-0.01838391,0.02209979,-0.06308215,0.03595312,0.00259137,0.06424054,0.03888389,0.00388951,0.08578040,0.05123891,-0.04047281,0.05204603,0.06347965,-0.03351413]',E'Explanation\n\nFor a [PostgreSQL](https://hub.docker.com/_/postgres) image, that image will package the database binaries, config files, and other dependencies. For a Python web app, it''ll include the Python runtime, your app code, and all of its dependencies.\n\nThere are two important principles of images:\n\n1. Images are immutable. Once an image is created, it can''t be modified. You can only make a new image or add changes on top of it.','{"source": "docker", "version": "27", "language": "dockerfile", "title": "What Is An Image", "section_title": "what-is-an-image", "url": "https://github.com/docker/docs/blob/main/content/get-started/docker-concepts/the-basics/what-is-an-image.md", "topics": "docker,container,what,is,an,image", "categories": "devops,containers,deployment"}');
