.17524211,-0.07066389,-0.02031045,-0.02070783,-0.01476956,0.00906288,-0.00533706,0.10065169,0.06637546,0.02801848,0.00424771,-0.02773728,-0.03380703,0.01501176,0.03516452,0.05775369,-0.00326925,-0.03877830,-0.01025938,-0.04827307,-0.03067691,0.00767741,0.00720789,-0.05305561,0.03937046,-0.02439543,-0.03062567,0.01022386,-0.00551795,-0.01013935,0.01499613,-0.04034606,0.06427906,0.02598264,-0.04654856,-0.00394161,0.04063177,0.07478433,0.05900132,0.00453346,0.06553659,0.05631266,0.03255615]',E'Explanation\n\n2. Container images are composed of layers. Each layer represents a set of file system changes that add, remove, or modify files.\n\nThese two principles let you to extend or add to existing images. For example, if you are building a Python app, you can start from the [Python image](https://hub.docker.com/_/python) and add additional layers to install your app''s dependencies and add your code. This lets you focus on your app, rather than Python itself.','{"source": "docker", "version": "27", "language": "dockerfile", "title": "What Is An Image", "section_title": "what-is-an-image", "url": "https://github.com/docker/docs/blob/main/content/get-started/docker-concepts/the-basics/what-is-an-image.md", "topics": "docker,container,what,is,an,image", "categories": "devops,containers,deployment"}');
