35018,-0.06617979,-0.01192041,0.05506884,-0.01313229,0.00742798,0.02815228,0.08072482,0.05254128,0.03539326,0.02672204,-0.05066441,-0.01327680,0.04771966,0.04686941,0.02749937,-0.04416663,-0.06822310,-0.02052876,-0.00582217,-0.00579488,0.03222231,0.01433637,-0.09560759,0.03392273,0.02131797,-0.00004889,-0.01177929,-0.04266430,-0.03149619,-0.02846680,-0.07915045,0.03462605,0.05150360,0.03990065,0.00901698,0.02833731,0.02832378,0.01827489,-0.00453894,0.09601565,0.04506459,0.08023930]',E'Build an app image\n\nNow that you have a base image, you can extend that image to build additional images.\n\n1. Start a new container using the newly created node-base image:\n\n    ```console\n    $ docker run --name=app-container -ti node-base\n    ```\n\n2. Inside of this container, run the following command to create a Node program:\n\n    ```console\n    $ echo ''console.log("Hello from an app")'' > app.js\n    ```\n\n    To run this Node program, you can use the following command and see the message printed on the screen:','{"source": "docker", "version": "27", "language": "dockerfile", "title": "Understanding Image Layers", "section_title": "understanding-image-layers", "url": "https://github.com/docker/docs/blob/main/content/get-started/docker-concepts/building-images/understanding-image-layers.md", "topics": "docker,container,understanding,image,layers", "categories": "devops,containers,deployment"}');
